// Sutra tutorial — a walk through every primitive class, annotated
// with what the compiler does to each one.
//
// ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// How the compiler thinks about this program
// ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Sutra has no runtime control flow. No if/else at runtime. No
// branches in the compute path. Every operation is a tensor op.
//
// The compiler takes this file and expands every operator, method,
// and function through symbolic substitution until the whole
// program is one enormous algebraic expression over tensors. Then
// it simplifies — fold constants, collapse compositions, cancel
// inverses — aiming at the theoretical limit of one matrix
// multiplication per program. (The current compiler does some of
// these folds; the full fusion is ongoing work.)
//
// Everything that feels like control flow — hashmap lookups, if
// statements, array indexing, loops — is math underneath. Below
// you'll see them all, with a comment on what the compiler turns
// them into.
//
// Locally, computing 2 + 3 by adding two 868-dimensional vectors
// is absurd. Globally, that uniformity is what lets the compiler
// fuse the whole program into one kernel chain.


// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// 1. Number-axis primitives: int, float, complex
// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
// int, float, and complex all live on the same real/imag synthetic
// axes. The class tag controls what the compiler lets you write;
// the runtime representation is identical.

// Literal 2 and 3 are integer constants. Compile-time constant
// folding turns `2 + 3` into the literal 5 before codegen sees it.
int total = 2 + 3;

// Float has the fractional bits. Compile-time literal, same axis.
float pi_approx = 3.14159;

// Imaginary-suffix literal: `5i` is one token, not `5 * i`.
// `5 + 5i` folds at simplify time into ComplexLiteral(5, 5) — one
// make_complex allocation at runtime, not a runtime add.
complex c = 5 + 5i;

// Complex multiplication is NOT element-wise. It's a composition
// of three cached matrices + one element-wise multiply, computed
// as tensor operations so the simplifier can fuse chains of these.
complex product = c * (3 + 2i);


// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// 2. Char literals
// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
// A char is an int with a flag bit. Code point on the real axis,
// a 1.0 on synthetic[AXIS_CHAR_FLAG]. Same storage as int; the
// flag distinguishes 'a' from the plain int 97 at runtime.

char letter = 'a';


// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// 3. Truth-axis primitives: bool, fuzzy, trit
// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
// Three views of one axis — synthetic[AXIS_TRUTH]. The value is
// a real number in [-1, +1]. false = -1, unknown = 0, true = +1.
// The class tag controls what defuzzification will do and what
// literals the compiler accepts.

// `true` / `false` compile to make_truth(+1.0) / make_truth(-1.0).
// Not Python bool — a truth-axis vector.
bool ready = true;

// `fuzzy f = 0.7` compiles to `make_truth(0.7)` — one allocation,
// the literal never becomes a Python float at runtime.
fuzzy confidence = 0.7;

// `unknown` (or `unk`) is the neutral point on the truth axis.
// `trit` is a truth-axis value with {-1, 0, +1} as first-class
// attractors under defuzzify.
trit verdict = unknown;


// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// 4. Logical operations — polynomial, no branches
// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
// &&, ||, ! on truth-axis values are degree-4 (for AND/OR) and
// degree-1 (for NOT) polynomials. Exact on the three-valued grid
// {-1, 0, +1}, smooth everywhere else. No abs, no sign, no kink.
// Compile-time simplifier can fold nested compositions.

// AND: (a + b + ab − a² − b² + a²b²) / 2 — element-wise on tensors.
fuzzy both_conditions = confidence && ready;

// OR, symmetrically.
fuzzy either_condition = confidence || ready;

// NOT is multiplication by -1 — the single linear op on this axis.
fuzzy flipped = !confidence;


// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// 5. Derived connectives collapse to products
// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
// Written as compositions, XOR and IFF reduce algebraically to
// single monomials on the signed truth scale:
//
//     xor(a, b) = (a && !b) || (!a && b)   =   -a · b
//     iff(a, b) = (a → b) && (b → a)       =    a · b
//
// The compiler doesn't yet recognize this pattern at
// simplification time, so the emitted code evaluates all five
// polynomial primitives. A future simplifier pass would reduce
// this to one multiplication.

fuzzy disagreement = (confidence && !ready) || (!confidence && ready);


// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// 6. Ordered comparison — differentiable, number-axis only
// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
// >, <, >=, <= project both sides onto the real axis, subtract,
// and pass the result through tanh(100 · diff). Differentiable
// everywhere, saturates at ±1 for any noticeable difference.
// Strict and non-strict forms collapse on this scheme — tanh(0)
// is 0 regardless, so ties give unknown in both.

fuzzy has_enough = total > 3;


// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// 7. Equality — cosine similarity on vectors
// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
// == and != work on any two vectors. Computes cosine similarity
// via pure tensor arithmetic (dot product + norms + divide) and
// places the scalar on the truth axis as a fuzzy.

// These strings auto-embed — bare string literals in a vector slot
// compile to _VSA.embed("...") against the Ollama-backed codebook,
// batched into one prefetch at module init.
vector cat  = "cat";
vector dog  = "dog";
vector kitty = "cat";

fuzzy same_concept = cat == kitty;       // ≈ +1
fuzzy near_concept = cat == dog;         // ≈ +0.7 (semantic neighbors)


// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// 8. Defuzzify — sharpen fuzzy back to discrete
// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
// defuzzy(x) projects any value onto the truth axis (matmul with
// _truth_projector), then iterates `x == true` 10 times. Under
// cosine equality that snaps non-zero truths to ±1; zeroes stay 0.
// Output is a three-valued bool.

bool is_sharp = defuzzy(confidence);


// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// 9. Hashmaps — rotation binding + additive superposition
// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
// A hashmap is NOT a dictionary lookup. It's one vector built by
// summing bind(key, value) for every pair. Retrieval is
// unbind(key, storage) — a matrix multiplication followed by
// argmax-cosine against a codebook. No hashing, no bucket
// dispatch, no pointer follow. Pure math.

map<vector, string> LABEL = {
    cat:     "feline",
    dog:     "canine"
};


// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// 10. The IO boundary — strings at the edge
// ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
//
// Strings in Sutra exist only at two places: as source-code
// literals (which auto-embed when the slot wants a vector), and at
// the final return where the program hands results back to the
// host. Everywhere in between, the string has already become a
// vector. The map lookup below is the one place a real Python
// string surfaces in the emitted code.

function string main() {
    // Use every declared variable so the compiler sees them all.
    // These usages compose into the final computation; the
    // simplifier folds what it can.

    // Number-axis variables threaded through arithmetic.
    int summary_int = total + 0;            // uses `total`
    float summary_f = pi_approx * 1.0;      // uses `pi_approx`
    complex summary_c = c + product;        // uses `c` and `product`
    int letter_code = letter;               // uses `letter` — same axis, just retagged

    // Truth-axis variables combined through polynomial logic.
    fuzzy truth_blend =
        (both_conditions && either_condition) ||
        flipped ||
        disagreement ||
        has_enough;
    bool verdict_sharp = defuzzy(verdict);  // uses `verdict`
    bool confidence_sharp = is_sharp;       // uses `is_sharp`

    // Equality results folded into a summary.
    fuzzy match_strength = same_concept || near_concept;

    // Fold everything into one combined fuzzy so the compiler sees
    // one dataflow. (A future simplifier could collapse this whole
    // chain into a small tensor expression.)
    fuzzy combined = truth_blend && match_strength;

    // Suppress "unused" concerns for the number-axis values by
    // combining them symbolically. A real compile-time simplifier
    // would fold the whole expression since everything is constant.
    int combined_int = summary_int + letter_code;    // 5 + 97 = 102
    float combined_f = summary_f * 1.0;               // 3.14159
    complex combined_c = summary_c * 1i;              // rotate by i

    // The one real string lookup. `argmax_cosine` compares `cat`
    // against the codebook and returns the closest vector;
    // LABEL[winner] is a vector-keyed map using identity-first
    // lookup. The result is the one Python string in the
    // compiled program's output path.
    vector winner = argmax_cosine(cat, [cat, dog]);
    return LABEL[winner];
}
